    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right, sourdough starters are fascinating biological ecosystems. The activity starts with wild yeast and bacteria from the environment, which proliferate twice each day when you feed them. The process creates lactic acid, carbon dioxide, and other organic acids, producing that characteristic tangy flavor as well as resulting in the batter swollen with gases.\n\nIt can indeed seem unpredictable, but this natural fermentation is quite common. Sometimes the yeast need a bit more oxygen to build up (especially at the beginning), or they might go dormant if under stress. Yet when they receive the right environment and nutrients, they become suddenly lively and hearty, causing the said \"explosion,\" as you described.\n\nDuring these flares of activity, your starter may tip over in its container due to the gas production, or it might simply double its volume surprisingly quickly, which can be both impressive and intimidating. Remember, each day you're providing food for them; it might not be visually apparent, but they're definitely busy hard at work. As long as you continue to feed it and maintain a stable, warm environment, your starter will eventually reach the point where it reliably doubles in size with each feed. For now, enjoy watching it adapt and grow, and in due time, it will",
